Untitled Page 31

Saturday, January 1, 1944

Spent the morning and part of the afternoon doing curatorial work in the basement. Put specimens away. Identified some of Tony Green's material from Guadal canal. Other miscellaneous work. Did a little work on Coleonyx but not much as am still waiting for USNM, Field, and Gloyd specimens.

Page Edit History:
  • jgoldenberg 01/26/2012 01:04 PM

Sunday, January 2, 1944

Spent the day in curatorial work. Didn't get much done. Chas. Shaw called with his new wife Jane Joan B.

Friday, January 7, 1944

Drove to Los Angeles this morning to attend an Army-Navy Conference at the Ambassador Hotel.

Attended the converence all afternoon. Heard talks by Patterson (???under deey of war???), Gen HH Arnold, Gen FF Armstrong, Col. Nance, and Col. Ruddell. There were also fine "restricted" war movies. It was a very impressive conference.

In the evening I we had a buffet supper and then a vaudeville show at Warner Bros. Studios At the supper saw among others: Allan Hale, Donald Crisp, Gary Cooper, Robt. Montgomery, Ann Sheridan, Joan Crawford, Geo O Brien, Ida Lupino, Linda Basquette, Sidney Greensheet, Errol Flynn.

The performers Jack Carson, Abbot & Costello, Jane ???Myman???, Reggy Gardner, Bob Allen, Bette Davis, Frank Sinatra, Irene Mamey, Ray Bolger, Jack Benny, Dinah Shore, Spike Jones & his City Slickers.

The trip to and from Warners in busses with military ???outriders??? was something in itself.

Notes:

lwilliams

???under deey of war???

lwilliams

???under deey of war??? ???outriders???

Page Edit History:
  • jgoldenberg 07/09/2012 06:55 PM

Saturday, January 8, 1944

In attendance at the war conference all day. Speakers: Admr Halsey, Vice Ad. McCain, Col. O'Donnell, Col. Warren J. Clear (the highlight of the meting) Gen. Holcombs, Col. ER Hagemah, Gen. Styer, Gen. Knudsen, Rear Admr. Blandy, Col. Collins.

In the evening we went to an interesting and impressive public exhibition at the Coliseum.

Returned from Los Angeles in the morning.

Worked all afternoon and evening to catch up.

Saturday, February 12, 1944

Sunday, February 13, 1944

Finished counting Gloyd's Coleonyx. Then overhauled the variegatus and brevis sections of the paper to incorporate the Gloyd and MVZ material. Practically finished this, and also almost finished brevis. Made good progress, the first in many weeks.

Saturday, February 19, 1944

Worked all day and evening on Coleonyx. Counted USNM from Guatemala and Field elegans and mitratus. Was disappointed to find I had a smaller USNM series than I expected. This will cause a further delay.

Saturday, March 11, 1944

Made some headway with the Mexican and Central American Coleonyx although seriously handicapped by the lack of the USNM specimens. Went to a meeting of the Zoo directors this noon - - took several hours.

Sunday, March 12, 1944

Worked all day and evening (except concert in the afternoon - called for Wallensetein at his hotel) on the tubercular forms of Coleonyx and made better progress than yesterday. Little more can be done now until the USNM specimens arrive.

Saturday, March 18, 1944

Finished the write-up of Coleonyx mitratus ungulatus. This is as far as I can go with Coleonyx until the arrival of the USNM specimens. They have been shipped.

Glanced at some worm-snake problems.

Saturday, March 25, 1944

Counted the newly arrived USNM specimens of Coleonyx. Then rewrote elegans elegans and nemoralis to incorporate the new material. Made good progress.

Went to a piano concert in the evening.

Sunday, March 26, 1944

Finished the re-writing of the mitratus section of the Coleonyx paper and thus practically completed the entire paper, except a summary and conclusions, and similar frills.

Spent the evening on state income tax.

Saturday, April 1, 1944

Spent the afternoon packing the borrowed specimens for return.

Saturday, April 8, 1944

Sunday, April 9, 1944

Worked all day on Arizona and finished the description of eburnata except that the allocation of material outside the area of the type series is still pretty weak. GG found a large ring neck in the garden today, evidently killed by a cat.

Saturday, April 29, 1944

Spent the day on Pituophis from Lower California and made good progress, except had to go out in the evening. Discovered the parallel dark bars on the underside of the tail in the San Martin Island form and several items which might make the Cedros form a good subspecies. Bimaris looks ok but it will take further checking to segregate them from the Mojave desert specimens. Am badly handicapped by not having the CAS specimens.

Saturday, May 13, 1944

Zoo meeting this noon. Checked some rattlers loaned by AMNH. Then worked on Pituophis; discovered the principal difference between deserticola and affinis the black vs. brown anterior blotches. This seems quite consistent in a large number of specimens.

(May 14 Continued)
These last two were found at the same time but on opposite sides of the road.

1 shovel noseLCOR4 mi W of The Narrows10:1267(deg)
1Long noseLCORScissor's Crossing10:4362(deg)
1Long noseMDORScissor's Crossing
1Long noseLDORBanner (near cattle ground)large bands, nearer clarus

Reached home at 1:30. Total evening drive 36 miles; 2hrs, 5min. A very disappointing evening b/c cold and high wind.

Sunday, May 14, 1944

Peckham died last night. Nothing done this morning except segregated some Arizona specimens. Too busy to do any herp work in the afternoon.

This afternoon at 4:20 started for the desert with Dave and Capt. Mott. It was cool and windy getting worse as we proceeded eastward.

1Banded King LDORFoster (new road)Grass
1Gopher SmallDOR (saved)Pine Hills Jnct.Grass

Reached Scissors Crossing at 7:20 (War Time) Sundown. Windy and cold. 60deg.

1LongnoseDORFoot of Sentenac30 spots on body. Plenty red. Clearly a lecontei.

Reached the County Line at 8:40. Warm wind. 77deg. Only a little light left in the west.

1Shovel nose LCOR2 mi. W. of Bensons9:0574degStrong wind
1Coleonyx LCOR3 mi. W. of Bensons9:1274deg"

Saturday, June 3, 1944

Spent the morning entering in the large record book the data on CAS specimens accumulated last week in SF. Then in the afternoon studied the relationship of affinis and deserticola and reached the conclusion they surely intergrade in two places - probably more. This is important in the relationships of Lower California species.

Saturday, August 5, 1944

Spent the day at Stanford 9:30 to 5:00. Made lists of their Pituophis, Arizona, and Masticophis lateralis. Surveyed the material. Made many blotch counts on Pituophis. On the whole did quite well. Talked with Margaret Storey.

Worked on newly arrived USNM Pituophis this morning and then discovered that the shipment which had just arrived was incomplete. Spent the rest of the day and evening on Arizona tabulations and made good headway on this dreary but necessary work.

Sunday, December 10, 1944

Spent the morning on Arizona synonymy. Did the whole thing over again in the view of the latest division into subspecies. Spent the afternoon checking and rearranging specimens; also rewriting the tabulations. Progress not too good.

Saturday, December 16, 1944

Worked all day and evening on Arizona. Counted a few specimens; the rest of the time tabulating. Also made up a bibliography of my papers for grant.

Page Edit History:
  • jgoldenberg 07/09/2012 06:45 PM
  • BPOC 07/18/2011 05:00 PM

Sunday, December 17, 1944

Worked all day and evening on Arizona and made fair headway, mostly on tail lengths. Discovered for the first time that philipi was especially long-tailed. Philip arrived by plane this evening.
